  "Let's start off with the most basic example, alerting <span class=\"sparkle_wrapper__cL2jQ\"><span class=\"sparkle_sparkle_wrapper__Izdcu\" style=\"top:35%;left:2%\"><svg class=\"sparkle_sparkle_svg__WdZ3Y\" fill=\"none\" height=\"19\" viewbox=\"0 0 68 68\" width=\"19\"><path d=\"M 48 5 L 51 27 L 74 30 L 51 33 L 48 56 L 44 33 L 23 30 L 44 27 Z\" fill=\"var(--yellow)\"></path></svg></span><span class=\"sparkle_sparkle_wrapper__Izdcu\" style=\"top:89%;left:5%\"><svg class=\"sparkle_sparkle_svg__WdZ3Y\" fill=\"none\" height=\"15\" viewbox=\"0 0 68 68\" width=\"15\"><path d=\"M 48 5 L 51 27 L 74 30 L 51 33 L 48 56 L 44 33 L 23 30 L 44 27 Z\" fill=\"var(--yellow)\"></path></svg></span><strong class=\"sparkle_child_wrapper__bem0y\">OUCH</strong></span> whenever a user clicks on a button.": "",
  "Next, you'll notice that we're passing our event handler as a <em metastring=\"\">reference</em> to <code>onClick</code>, not as an <em metastring=\"\">invocation</em>. Note the difference between these two <code>onClick</code> props.": "",
  "If we pass <code>onClick</code> an <em metastring=\"\">invocation</em>, à la <code>handleClick()</code>, as soon as the JavaScript engine encounters the invocation, it will invoke the function and pass the return value to <code>onClick</code>. This is obviously not what we want.": "",
  "Instead, we want to pass <code>onClick</code> a <em metastring=\"\">reference</em> to the function, so that it can invoke the function when the event occurs.": "",
  "Next, you'll notice that we created our event handler <em metastring=\"\">inside</em> the component, not outside of it. This is also a common pattern, but it may feel unintuitive at first. Can you think of why we do this?": "",
  "We no longer have access to <code>message</code> via scope. Instead, we have to pass it as an argument to <code>handleClick</code>, which forces us to create <em metastring=\"\">another</em> function that we pass to <code>onClick</code>. This indirection is unnecessary and is a good indication that we should move <code>handleClick</code> back inside of our component so we can take advantage of lexical scoping.": "",
  "So at this point you know how to add a click handler to a <code>button</code> (which is <span class=\"font-black tracking-wider\" style=\"color:var(--blue)\">cool</span>), but let's look at a scenario that isn't straight out of a generic React tutorial.": "",
  "Now let's work on our event handler that we'll pass as an <button aria-controls=\"radix-:rau:\" aria-expanded=\"false\" aria-haspopup=\"dialog\" class=\"Popover_children__8p5Di\" data-state=\"closed\" type=\"button\"><span><code>onCopy</code></span> <svg class=\"fill-brand-purple dark:fill-brand-yellow w-2 h-2 b-2 mx-0.5 mb-4\" enable-background=\"new 0 0 455 455\" version=\"1.1\" viewbox=\"0 0 455 455\" x=\"0\" xml:space=\"preserve\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" y=\"0\"><path d=\"M347.49 227L454.5 165.212 394.508 61.288 287.5 123.077 287.5 0 167.5 0 167.5 123.077 60.492 61.288 0.499 165.212 107.51 227 0.5 288.788 60.492 392.712 167.5 330.923 167.5 455 287.5 455 287.5 330.923 394.508 392.712 454.501 288.788z\"></path></svg></button> prop to each of our three emojis.": "",
  "This does bring up a new scenario though. We now need to know some specific information about the event that was triggered. Specifically, we need to know <em metastring=\"\">which</em> emoji was copied so we can see if it was the right one.": ""
